section.p:
Note that the signs of the cofactors follow a "checkerboard pattern". Namely, the pattern of plus and minus signs in the (i,j)-th entry of the matrix
\mat{+ - + -; - + - +; + - + -; - + - +}
is the sign in the definition of C_{ij}.

statement.p:
We find the determinant of
      A= \mat{2 5 -3 -2;-2 -3 2 -5;1 3 -2 0;-1 6 4 0}.
      We expand along the last column to find
      \det A=2\det\mat{-2 -3 2;1 3 -2;-1 6 4}
      -5 \det \mat{2 5 -3;1 3 -2;-1 6 4}.
      We can find these two determinants by expanding them as well. For example, expanding along the first column on the first one, we find that


          & \det \mat{-2 -3 2;1 3 -2;-1 6 4}


          & = -2 \det \mat{3 -2;6 4} -\det \mat{-3 2;6 4} -\det \mat{-3 2;3 -2}


          & = -2 (24) -(-24) -0=-48+24+0=-24.


      Similarly, by expanding the second 3\times 3 matrix along the first column, we find that


        &
        \mat{2 5 -3;1 3 -2;-1 6 4}
        = 2 \det \mat{3 -2;6 4} -\det \mat{5 -3;6 4} -\det \mat{5 -3;3 -2}

        & = 2(24) -(38) -(-1) = 11.


      Thus, we find that
      \det A= 2(-24)-5(11)=-103.
